<!-- top of Dan Cole's column -->


<table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" class="tableborder">
<tr>
    <td bgcolor="#1B3D85" class="columnsubhead"><div align="center">A Message From Dan Cole</div></td>
</tr>
<tr>
    <td>
    <p align="center"><img src="/images/ces_photos/dan_cole.jpg" alt="Dan Cole"><br>
    <span class="subhead">Dan Cole</span><br>
    Vice President, Exhibitor Services, Sales and Business Development, International CES</p>
    <hr align="center" width="90%" size="1" noshade color="#999999">
    <!-- article start -->
    <p><strong>Five Tips. Four Days. One Reason.</strong><br> by Dan Cole</p>
    I realize you’re probably the busiest you’ve been all year, so I’m casting all lulling business analogies aside. Instead, I’m going to offer up five quick tips to help you plan your four days at CES, and I’m doing it all for one reason – and that’s your success. 
<OL type=1>
<LI>Register! Get this off of your to-do list now to save time on-site. Group registration allows you to upload a spreadsheet of names rather than registering each person one by one, and if you get this done before December 5, you’ll receive your badges in the mail.&nbsp; </LI>
<LI>Sanity check with SmartBooth. Never before have you had a better barometer than you do this year. Devote at least 30 minutes twice a week to check your SmartBooth portal. It’s there so you can check to see who’s checking on you and learn other interests of those planning to attend CES. It’s a great way to create a targeted marketing list; the success stories I’ve already heard with still a month to go before show doors even opens is astounding.&nbsp; </LI>
<LI>Get your keywords. Along the same lines, you can purchase keywords through SmartBooth. Think about this: about 80,000 people are already using their MyCES Personal Planners (the attendee side of SmartBooth) to search for show information. You can buy a search term to ensure your company information (booth, products and more) are at the top of the page. </LI>
<LI>The list of pre-registered press members and analysts is available. This will be an incredibly useful spreadsheet for you as you plan your PR strategy on-site. I know that many journalists are already booking appointments, so I’d suggest you line up your time with your key press targets now. </LI>
<LI>Although your day’s packed with 2007 CES details, the 2008 Exhibit Space Selection Packet is coming your way. Don’t let this slip to the bottom of your stack; you need this information this January. Look at it now and pack it with you when you hop your flight to Vegas. If you have any questions about space selection before January 8, e-mail <A href="mailto:sdevore@CE.org">sdevore@CE.org</A>. There you are. Five tips to gear up for what I hope will be the most productive and successful four days of your business year. </LI></OL>
    <!-- article end -->
    <img src="/images/general/dan_cole_sig.gif"><br>Dan Cole</p></td>
</tr>
</table>
